// TEST: effect_unhandled_no_handler_in_scope
// EXPECT: error E6005 at 25:3
// Section 10.3: a function that invokes an effect operation with NO Layer-1
// (`handling` block) and NO Layer-2 (`handle ... with`) handler in scope, and
// which does not declare the effect in its own `with` clause, is a
// compile-time error. Here `main` invokes the `Log` effect operation `log`
// with no handler installed and no `with Log` clause.
//
// Observed diagnostic: E6005 (effect operation called without its effect
// declared or handled), emitted by the resolver at the `log(...)` call site
// (25:3). The message names the op and its effect; the note states the fix
// (`with Log` on `main`, or a `handling` block). Historically this surfaced
// as the generic undefined-name E1001 with a misleading "did you mean `Log`?"
// suggestion (Q-diag-effect-violation-errors). Effect ops are in scope ONLY
// in handler-in-scope contexts (a `with` clause, an effect impl method, a
// `handling` block, or a module-level `handle`); with none present, the
// resolver recognizes the op name and reports the effect-system rule.
module effects_unhandled_effect_error

effect Log {
  fn log(message: String) -> Void
}

fn main() {
  log("no handler is installed for Log")
}
